            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Robert Miller\u2019s story began not under the California sun, but in the long shadow of a shuttered steel mill in western Pennsylvania. Raised in a working-class family that valued grit over report cards, he graduated high school in 1988 with few prospects beyond the town's slow, rusting decline. Lured by hazy stories of opportunity, he bought a one-way bus ticket to San Francisco, arriving with little more than a duffel bag and a romantic, ill-formed notion of reinvention.\n\nThe city, however, proved to be as harsh as it was beautiful. Robert spent his twenties and early thirties bouncing between construction jobs, restaurant kitchens, and long stretches of unemployment. The isolating freedom he sought became a trap, and he fell into a deep struggle with alcoholism that left him estranged from his family and living on the brink of homelessness. His turning point came not in a bolt of lightning, but in the quiet, non-judgmental office of a community clinic in the Mission District. There, a counselor\u2014a man whose story of recovery mirrored his own\u2014offered him a path forward.\n\nThat encounter ignited a new purpose. After achieving sobriety, Robert dedicated himself to paying forward the compassion he had received. He earned his peer support certification and secured a position at a social services center. Now, at 53, his life has a quiet, stable rhythm. He lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Outer Richmond, a neighborhood whose foggy tranquility he cherishes. His daily 4.8-mile commute on the Muni gives him time to prepare for a day spent guiding others through the same darkness he once navigated.\n\nRobert\u2019s social circle is small but strong, built on the foundations of recovery groups and friendships with colleagues. He never married, his energy focused instead on healing himself and his community. His dream isn\u2019t for wealth, but for continued stability and meaning. He hopes to simply remain a steady presence, a testament to the belief that the city that can break you is also the one that can help you put the pieces back together."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the diesel fumes and the sharp, unfamiliar scent of the sea as he stepped off the bus in 1988. The city was a wall of sound\u2014sirens, cable car bells\u2014and he clutched his duffel bag, a skinny kid from a silent, rusting town. He felt both thrilled and terrifyingly small. That specific feeling, of being an anonymous speck in a beautiful, indifferent machine, would define the lonely freedom he chased for years, the very start of his long fall and eventual climb back up.\n\n2.\nHe recalls a rainy Tuesday in the late '90s, sitting on a curb in the Tenderloin after being fired from another dishwashing job. The cheap whiskey in his coat wasn't warming him anymore. He watched the headlights blur on the wet street, feeling a shame so complete it was a physical weight. It wasn't about being broke; it was the chilling realization he had become invisible, a ghost haunting the city he'd dreamed of. That cold, hollow moment was the bottom he had to hit.\n\n3.\nHe can still feel the scuffed linoleum floor under his worn-out shoes at the Mission clinic, around 2002. He expected judgment but the counselor just listened, then slid a cup of lukewarm coffee across the desk. \"I've sat where you're sitting,\" the man said quietly. In that simple sentence, a crack appeared in his wall of shame. It wasn\u2019t pity; it was recognition. For the first time in a decade, he felt like a person worth saving, planting the tiny, stubborn seed of his own recovery.\n\n4.\nHe never forgets his first client, a young man with the same haunted eyes he remembered from his own mirror. It was around 2007, his hands sweating as he offered the kid a bottle of water. He didn't offer advice; he just listened. When the young man finally spoke, Robert felt not pity, but a profound, grounding sense of purpose. He was no longer just the recipient of grace but a channel for it. That day, his painful past finally transformed into his greatest strength.\n\n5.\nJust last week, on the 38 Geary home, he watched the fog roll into the Outer Richmond, turning streetlights into soft halos. The bus hummed, a familiar rhythm carrying him toward his quiet apartment. There was no grand triumph, just a deep, bone-weary gratitude for this simple predictability. The kid who arrived in 1988 wanted fireworks; the man he became, at 53, was just thankful for the steady, quiet light in the fog\u2014a peace he had worked half a lifetime to earn."
